#. type: Title ==
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:380
#, no-wrap
msgid "GBIF dataset types for primary biodiversity data"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:385
msgid "In this presentation, you will review https://www.gbif.org/dataset-classes[primary biodiversity data^] that can be shared within GBIF."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block +
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:393
#, no-wrap
msgid "<div class=\"responsive-slides\">\n"
"  <iframe src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vQzx1KkR8aX3a8TyMk5I9PbRU-7pQIglMDXOssXq9zw7HROxvRH1Pxuqoj8as4J0Q/embed?start=false&loop=false\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"true\"></iframe>\n"
"</div>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:409
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide1.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:412
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 1 - GBIF dataset types for primary biodiversity data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:414
msgid "In this presentation, we’ll have a look at the different types of data that can be called ‘primary biodiversity data’ and shared within GBIF. These data can be complex and have different origins ; we’ll see how they can be structured into one of the three data classes accepted by GBIF, based on the Darwin Core data sharing standard that is used within the GBIF community."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:415
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide2.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:418
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 2 - Data richness levels supported by GBIF*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:420
msgid "GBIF currently supports four types of dataset:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:422
msgid "The first is dataset metadata – this is a dataset that allows you to provide descriptive information about a dataset.  You may use this type when you have not yet digitized your collection."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:424
msgid "The second type are species checklists. This allows you to share information on species including the countries and areas where they are found."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:426
msgid "The third type is for occurrence-only data.  This is data for species that includes names, dates and coordinates – the what, when and where of your data."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:428
msgid "The last type is Sampling-event data. This allows you to share even more data. You can share species with dates, coordinates, methods, abundance and even absence."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:429
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide3.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:432
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 3 - Checklists and taxonomical resources*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:434
msgid "The first type of dataset that can be published within GBIF is the checklist, aka a list of species or higher taxa. In a checklist, the main unit is the taxon, not the occurrence (individual)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:435
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide4.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:438
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 4 - Checklists and other taxonomical resources*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:440
msgid "Checklists, and more generally, taxonomical datasets can vary in scope:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:444
msgid "a list of species present in a protected area is a checklist, a national or thematic list of taxa (e.g. Butterflies of Laos, or the Flora of Malaysia), which sometimes provide more info on the distribution, taxonomical hierarchy and synonyms of the taxa is a checklist.  IUCN red lists (at the international, national or regional levels) also are checklists and can give more information about the vulnerability status of the listed taxa."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:445
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide5.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:448
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 5 - GBIF template for taxon data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:450
msgid "GBIF provides data publishers with templates for each class of dataset. The GBIF template for checklists (taxon Data) allows you to share information linked to each species or taxa : its id, full name and authorship, relationship to other taxa, geographical details and so on. In this template, one line represents one taxon and a taxon can only appear once in the dataset (otherwise it will create a duplicate)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:451
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide6.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:454
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 6 - Specimens and natural history collections materials*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:456
msgid "the second type of data that can be published within GBIF is data coming from natural history or scientific collections, also known as specimens. Unlike checklists, the main unit in a specimen collection will be the specimen (a single organism or group of organisms), and you can have multiple specimens from the same species or taxon group."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:457
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide7.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:460
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 7 - Specimens and collections materials*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:462
msgid "collections and specimens vastly differ in numbers, size and preservation methods. However, any kind of collection that holds preserved living organisms can be captured and shared within GBIF ; herbarium or zoological collections (including fossils) for example, but geology or human artifacts collections do not fall under the GBIF scope."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:463
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide8.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:466
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 8 - Literature*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:468
#, no-wrap
msgid " Biodiversity data can also be found in technical and scientific literature : it is possible to compile and share this kind of data within GBIF, but you should be extra-cautious not to share duplicate data (for example, a specimen described in a scientific article might already be present on GBIF.org in the dataset of its collection).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:469
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide9.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:472
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 9 - Examples of literature documents*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:474
msgid "In the absence of digitized datasets, biodiversity data can be extracted and compiled from scientific articles, phD or master theses, reports and other documents. ALWAYS contact the data owner first when compiling literature data to ask for permission to publish them to GBIF."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:475
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide10.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:478
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 10 - Fieldwork records and notes*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:480
msgid "A large majority of the data available on GBIF.org now comes from fieldwork records. These data can be observed and/or collected using different protocols in the field, by scientists, naturalists or amateur citizen-scientists via programmes and apps."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:481
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide11.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:484
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 11 - Fieldwork records and notes*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:486
#, no-wrap
msgid " These field data can be compiled in survey reports, environmental impact assessment studies, field notes and other logs. They can be linked to other types of data, such as checklists, which are complementary to occurrence data observed or collected in the wilderness.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:487
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide12.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:490
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 12 - GBIF template for occurrence data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:492
msgid "Occurrence data represents the GBIF class of datasets with the largest number of records on GBIF.org. Collection (aka specimens), literature and fieldwork data can be shared within GBIF using this template, which focuses on the observed individual or collected specimen. In this kind of dataset, multiple individuals or specimens can be recorded for a single taxon, as long as they each have a unique identifier. Other fields for occurrence data include where, when, how and by whom was each occurrence observed and/or collected in the field."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:493
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide13.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:496
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 13 - Event data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:498
msgid "Event data is a class of datasets that was added on GBIF.org in 2015.  They allow data publishers to share more information about the context of the observation or collection of specimens, and to group occurrences linked to the same event."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:499
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide14.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:502
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 14 - GBIF template for event data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:504
msgid "The GBIF template for Event data allows data publishers to share more information about the context of a biodiversity data collecting/recording event such as camera traps, insect traps, botanical relevés, birding sites and so on. Its structure is a bit more complex than the Taxonomical datasets and Occurrence datasets as it involves two files (e.g., two tabs in a spreadsheet) : one for describing the ‘events’ (e.g. each trap) and the other one to describe the specimens or occurrences linked to each event."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:505
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide15.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:508
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 15 - Other origins of data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:510
msgid "Sometimes, additional information or data can be found using other source materials than those previously mentioned in this video."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:511
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide16.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:514
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 16 - Other origins of data*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:516
msgid "These other sources include remote sensing tools, maps and satellite data, and other information supports such as pictures, audio and video recordings of wildlife. Most of the time, the information retrieved this way is supplemental to existing data but can provide valuable information about individuals and their location, habitat, migratory routes, etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:517
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide17.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:520
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 17 - Origins of data and Darwin Core concepts*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:522
msgid "In the following slides, we will see how the Darwin Core standard works with different types of data, and how to choose the dataset class that best fits a given dataset."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:523
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide18.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:526
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 18 - Darwin Core standard: cores and extensions*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:528
msgid "As you learned in the Darwin Core presentation, Darwin Core is a data sharing standard developed by the Biodiversity Information Standards (TDWG) organization, and is widely used to publish data within the extended GBIF community. Depending on the type of dataset with which you work, you’ll have to choose one of its three Cores (Occurrence, Taxon or Event Core), which can be linked to one or more Extensions to share more information (such as multimedia links, variables, identification history and so on). In some cases, a core can be used as an extension linked to another core: that is the case when publishing Event data, where one can use the Event Core to describe the sampled areas and then use the Occurrence Core as an Extension to share the specimens or individuals recorded."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:529
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide19.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:532
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 19 - Darwin Core standard: cores and extensions*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:534
msgid "Once the data has been standardized using the Darwin Core standard, each class of dataset (metadata-only, sampling event, taxonomic or occurrence datasets) can be published on GBIF.org using one of the tools mentioned on this figure. The most frequently used tool within the GBIF community is the GBIF-developed Integrated Publishing Toolkit (IPT), which transforms the source data into Darwin Core archives that are then harvested and indexed by GBIF. The data are then searchable and downloadable via GBIF.org."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:535
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide20.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:538
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 20 - Data quality requirements associated with each class*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:540
msgid "GBIF’s data quality requirements describe what you should provide for each dataset class. It doesn’t mean that the data won’t be indexed if some values are missing, but these requirements summarize what can be considered meaningful information for each class. You can of course share more."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:542
msgid "Some requirements are required (such as the occurrenceID, taxonID or eventID, depending on the type of dataset), others are optional but strongly recommended (such as coordinates in decimal degrees). You can find these requirements on GBIF.org."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:543
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide21.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:546
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 21 - How to choose a dataset type?*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:548
msgid "Choosing a dataset class can take some time, especially if you’re new to data publishing within GBIF. The GBIF helpdesk team created this useful flowchart which can be found on the GBIF Data Blog if you need further support to decide."
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:549
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide22.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:552
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 22 - Discussion*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:554
msgid "In order to be able to publish data to GBIF, it is important to understand the differences between the dataset classes at the early stages of the data capture and data managing process. You can reflect on this topic with the following questions:"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block *
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:556
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:713
msgid "With what kind of data do you work?"
msgstr "你工作上是使用怎樣的資料類型？"

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:558
msgid "Is your data type different than you originally thought?"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:560
msgid "How would you publish them to GBIF? (using which Core and/or extension?)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:561
#, no-wrap
msgid "data-mobilization::capture-dataset-types-Slide23.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:564
#, no-wrap
msgid "*Slide 23 - Conclusion*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:566
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:936
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/management.adoc:206
msgid "This is part of a series of presentations used in the GBIF Biodiversity Data Mobilization course. The biodiversity data mobilization curriculum was originally developed as part of the Biodiversity Information Development Programme funded by the European Union."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:568
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:938
msgid "This presentation was originally created and narrated by Sophie Pamerlon with additional contributions by BID and BIFA Trainers, Mentors and Students."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:572
#, no-wrap
msgid "Exercise 1b"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:577
msgid "Quiz yourself on the concepts covered in the dataset types presentation. There may be multiple correct answers for some questions."
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block =
#: en/data-mobilization/modules/ROOT/pages/capture.adoc:579
